      "content": "Of course, let's leave the goblins behind and focus on the math. The interest on your student loan is calculated using a simple formula: Interest = Principal Balance x Interest Rate. Each month, the interest is calculated based on the remaining principal balance. So, if you have a principal balance of $10,000 and an annual interest rate of 5%, the monthly interest would be $10,000 x 0.05 / 12 = $41.67. This interest amount is added to your monthly payment, which then goes towards both the interest and the principal. As you continue to make payments, the principal balance decreases, which in turn reduces the interest calculated each month. I hope this clears things up!",
